events.plain_body:
Hello Terry!
&nbsp;
We were reviewing this ticket with my team and we found two possible solutions:&nbsp;
  Configure the application as multi-tenant  Use a tenant-specific endpoint  &nbsp;
Knowing that you may not want to have this as a multi-tenant app you could try to configure a tenant-specific endpoint: A tenant-specific endpoint is specific to a particular organization or tenant. To do this, you will need to modify your API call to use the endpoint that corresponds to the organization where the Salesforce and OneDrive integration is taking place. You can obtain the tenant-specific endpoint from the Azure Active Directory (AAD) portal or the OneDrive API documentation.
&nbsp;
To obtain the tenant-specific endpoint from the Azure Active Directory (AAD) portal, you can follow these steps:
&nbsp;
  Sign in to the Azure portal using your Azure AD administrator account.  Navigate to the "Azure Active Directory" section.  In the left-hand menu, select "App registrations" where your application is registered.  Locate and select your application from the list.  On the application overview page, you should find the "Endpoints" section. Look for the "Federation Metadata Document" URL or the "OpenID Connect metadata document" URL. Both of these URLs should contain the tenant-specific endpoint.  &nbsp;

&nbsp;
The URL will have the following format: "https://login.microsoftonline.com/{tenant-id}/". The {tenant-id} part represents the specific organization's Azure AD tenant.
&nbsp;

Hi Terry,
&nbsp;
Here is our suggestion on how your developers might try to solve it; keep in mind that since this falls outside our regular support, the solutions might require additional research from your development team:&nbsp;
&nbsp;
  Configure the application as multi-tenant  Use a tenant-specific endpoint  &nbsp;
Knowing that you may not want this as a multi-tenant app, you could configure a tenant-specific endpoint: A tenant-specific endpoint is specific to a particular organization or tenant.
&nbsp;
To do this, you must modify your API call to use the endpoint corresponding to the organization where the Salesforce and OneDrive integration is taking place.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
You can obtain the tenant-specific endpoint from the Azure Active Directory (AAD) portal or the OneDrive API documentation.
&nbsp;
Here you go (see below the steps)
&nbsp;

&nbsp;
Here are the steps we followed to get the image above to obtain the tenant-specific endpoint from the Azure Active Directory (AAD) portal; you can follow these steps:
&nbsp;
  Sign in to the Azure portal using your Azure AD administrator account.  Next, navigate to the "Azure Active Directory" section.  In the left-hand menu, select "App registrations," where your application is registered.  Locate and select your application from the list.  You should find the "Endpoints" section on the application overview page. Look for the "Federation Metadata Document" URL or the "OpenID Connect metadata document" URL. Both of these URLs should contain the tenant-specific endpoint.  
The URL will have the following format:
&nbsp;
"https://login.microsoftonline.com/{tenant-id}/." The {tenant-id} part represents the specific organization's Azure AD tenant.

